approve(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-approve}. NOTE: If `value` is the maximum `uint256`, the allowance is not updated on `transferFrom`. This is semantically equivalent to an infinite approval. Requirements: - `spender` cannot be the zero address.

buy(uint256,uint256).details: Redirects to the internal function `_buyOrder` by passing the sender's address and deposit amount. Important: The Bancor Formula has an upper computational limit of (10^38). For tokens with 18 decimal places, this effectively leaves a maximum allowable deposit amount of (10^20). While this is substantially large, it is crucial to be aware of this constraint. Transactions exceeding this limit will be reverted.

params._depositAmount: The amount of collateral token depoisited.
params._minAmountOut: The minimum acceptable amount the user expects to receive from the transaction.

buyFor(address,uint256,uint256).details: Redirects to the internal function `_buyOrder` by passing the receiver address and deposit amount. Important: The Bancor Formula has an upper computational limit of (10^38). For tokens with 18 decimal places, this effectively leaves a maximum allowable deposit amount of (10^20). While this is substantially large, it is crucial to be aware of this constraint. Transactions exceeding this limit will be reverted.

params._depositAmount: The amount of collateral token depoisited.
params._minAmountOut: The minimum acceptable amount the user expects to receive from the transaction.
params._receiver: The address that will receive the bought tokens.

calculatePurchaseReturn(uint256).details: This function takes into account any applicable buy fees before computing the token amount to be minted. Revert when depositAmount is zero.

params._depositAmount: The amount of tokens deposited by the user.

returns.mintAmount: The amount of new tokens that will be minted as a result of the deposit.

calculateSaleReturn(uint256).details: This function takes into account any applicable sell fees before computing the collateral amount to be redeemed. Revert when depositAmount is zero.

params._depositAmount: The amount of tokens deposited by the user.

returns.redeemAmount: The amount of collateral that will be redeemed as a result of the deposit.

closeBuy().details: Only callable by the Orchestrator owner, or Manager.      Reverts if buying is already closed.

closeSell().details: Only callable by the Orchestrator owner, or Manager.      Reverts if selling is already closed.

decimals().details: Returns the decimals places of the token.

returns._0: uint The static price for buying the issuance token
uint The static price for selling the issuance token

getVirtualCollateralSupply().details: This function returns the virtual supply by calling the internal `_getVirtualCollateralSupply` function.

returns._0: The current virtual collateral supply as a uint.

getVirtualTokenSupply().details: This function returns the virtual supply by calling the internal `_getVirtualTokenSupply` function.

returns._0: The current virtual token supply as a uint.

identifier().details: The identifier is defined as the keccak256 hash of the module's      abi packed encoded major version, url and title.

init(address,(uint256,uint256,string,str.details: CAN be overriden by downstream contract.MUST call `__Module_init()`.

params.configData: Variable config data for specific module                   implementations.

isTrustedForwarder(address).details: We imitate here the EIP2771 Standard to enable metatransactions As it currently stands we dont want to feed the forwarder address to each module individually and we decided to move this to the orchestrator

params.forwarder: The contract address to be verified.

returns._0: bool Is the given address the trusted forwarder

mintIssuanceTokenTo(address,uint256).details: This function is restricted to be called only by the Orchestrator Owner.      It uses the internal _mint function to mint the tokens.

params._amount: The amount of tokens to be minted.
params._receiver: The address that will receive the newly minted tokens.

name().details: Returns the name of the token.

openBuy().details: Only callable by the Orchestrator owner, or Manager.      Reverts if buying is already open.

openSell().details: Only callable by the Orchestrator owner, or Manager.      Reverts if selling is already open.

sell(uint256,uint256).details: Redirects to the internal function `_sellOrder` by passing the sender's address and deposit amount. Important: The Bancor Formula has an upper computational limit of (10^26). For tokens with 18 decimal places, this effectively leaves a maximum allowable deposit amount of (10^8), or 100,000,000. Transactions exceeding this limit will be reverted.

params._depositAmount: The amount of issued token depoisited.
params._minAmountOut: The minimum acceptable amount the user expects to receive from the transaction.

sellFor(address,uint256,uint256).details: Redirects to the internal function `_sellOrder` by passing the receiver address and deposit amount. Important: The Bancor Formula has an upper computational limit of (10^26). For tokens with 18 decimal places, this effectively leaves a maximum allowable deposit amount of (10^8), or 100,000,000. Transactions exceeding this limit will be reverted.

params._depositAmount: The amount of issued token to deposited.
params._minAmountOut: The minimum acceptable amount the user expects to receive from the transaction.
params._receiver: The address that will receive the redeemed tokens.

setBuyFee(uint256).details: Only callable by the Orchestrator owner, or Manager.      The fee cannot exceed 10000 basis points. Reverts if an invalid fee is provided.

setReserveRatioForBuying(uint32).details: This function can only be called by the Orchestrator owner, or Manager.

params._reserveRatio: The new reserve ratio for buying, expressed in PPM.

setReserveRatioForSelling(uint32).details: This function can only be called by the Orchestrator owner, or Manager.

params._reserveRatio: The new reserve ratio for selling, expressed in PPM.

setSellFee(uint256).details: Only callable by the Orchestrator owner, or Manager.      The fee cannot exceed 10000 basis points. Reverts if an invalid fee is provided.

setVirtualCollateralSupply(uint256).details: This function should call the internal function `_setVirtualCollateralSupply`. The function must be implemented by the downstream contract. The downstream contract should manage access control for setting the supply.

params._virtualSupply: The new value to set for the virtual collateral supply.

setVirtualTokenSupply(uint256).details: This function calls the internal function `_setVirtualTokenSupply`. The function must be implemented by the downstream contract. The downstream contract should manage access control for setting the supply.

params._virtualSupply: The new value to set for the virtual token supply.

symbol().details: Returns the symbol of the token, usually a shorter version of the name.

transfer(address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transfer}. Requirements: - `to` cannot be the zero address. - the caller must have a balance of at least `value`.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).details: See {IERC20-transferFrom}. Emits an {Approval} event indicating the updated allowance. This is not required by the EIP. See the note at the beginning of {ERC20}. NOTE: Does not update the allowance if the current allowance is the maximum `uint256`. Requirements: - `from` and `to` cannot be the zero address. - `from` must have a balance of at least `value`. - the caller must have allowance for ``from``'s tokens of at least `value`.

buy(uint256,uint256).notice: Buy tokens for the sender's address. This function is subject to a transactional limit, determined by the deposit token's decimal precision and the underlying bonding curve algorithm.

buyFor(address,uint256,uint256).notice: Buy tokens on behalf of a specified receiver address. This function is subject to a transactional limit, determined by the deposit token's decimal precision and the underlying bonding curve algorithm.

calculatePurchaseReturn(uint256).notice: Calculates the amount of tokens to be minted based on a given deposit amount.

calculateSaleReturn(uint256).notice: Calculates the amount of tokens to be redeemed based on a given deposit amount.

closeBuy().notice: Closes the buying functionality for the token.

closeSell().notice: Closes the selling functionality for the collateral.

getReserveRatioForBuying().notice: Returns reserve ratio set for buying, used in the Bancor Formula contract

getReserveRatioForSelling().notice: Returns reserve ratio set for selling, used in the Bancor Formula contract

getStaticPriceForBuying().notice: Calculates and returns the static price for buying the issuance token. The return value is formatted in PPM.

getStaticPriceForSelling().notice: Calculates and returns the static price for selling the issuance token. The return value is formatted in PPM.

getVirtualCollateralSupply().notice: Returns the current virtual collateral supply.

getVirtualTokenSupply().notice: Returns the current virtual token supply.

isTrustedForwarder(address).notice: Checks if the provided address is the trusted forwarder

mintIssuanceTokenTo(address,uint256).notice: Mints a specified amount of Issuance Tokens to a designated receiver address.

openBuy().notice: Opens the buying functionality for the token.

openSell().notice: Opens the selling functionality for the collateral.

sell(uint256,uint256).notice: Sell collateral for the sender's address. This function is subject to a transactional limit, determined by the issuing token's decimal precision and the underlying bonding curve algorithm.

sellFor(address,uint256,uint256).notice: Redeem tokens on behalf of a specified receiver address. This function is subject to a transactional limit, determined by the issuing token's decimal precision and the underlying bonding curve algorithm.

setBuyFee(uint256).notice: Sets the fee percentage for buying tokens, payed in collateral

setReserveRatioForBuying(uint32).notice: Set the reserve ratio used for issuing tokens on a bonding curve.

setReserveRatioForSelling(uint32).notice: Set the reserve ratio used for redeeming tokens on a bonding curve.

setSellFee(uint256).notice: Sets the fee percentage for selling collateral, payed in collateral

setVirtualCollateralSupply(uint256).notice: Sets the virtual collateral supply to a new value.

setVirtualTokenSupply(uint256).notice: Sets the virtual token supply to a new value.
